  "text": " Hey guys, today we are going to use systems thinking to look at a physical system of an extensively discussed sustainability issue as a real working example. We will be looking at positive feedback loops within our chosen sustainability issue. For this educational video we will refer to the positive feedback loop as the reinforcing feedback loop to prevent any confusion. The name positive feedback loop is misleading as positive feedback loops do not necessarily have a positive i.e. good effect on a system or on its behaviour. It is also important to remember that a system is more than a sum of its parts and can exhibit adaptive, dynamic, goal-seeking, self-preserving and sometimes even evolutionary behaviour. Feedback loops are used to show how parts of a system interact and how these interactions can change over time. There are two types of feedback loops known as reinforcing and balancing. Balancing feedback loops are stabilising and goal-seeking because they oppose or reverse a change imposed on the system, keeping it balanced in dynamic equilibrium where the system does not change and is stable. Whereas reinforcing feedback loops are enhancing as it amplifies their direction of change imposed on a system, moving the system away from its equilibrium, they can either create runaway collapse or exponential growth of a system function or purpose. when the reinforcing feedback loops enhance or amplify the direction of change within a system the change or growth is far from a typical straight line slowly increasing Although it may look like a simple gradual increase for a period the growth will actually get faster and faster as the reinforcing feedback loop amplifies the direction of change and then amplifies this new direction of change and so on This is due to the self-enhancing trait of the reinforcing feedback loop. It is good to remember that systems with similar feedback structures produce similar dynamic behaviours, i.e. dominating reinforcing feedback loops will create exponential growth or runaway collapse. In a physical system, of which most sustainability issues are exponential growth, cannot last forever. And each exponentially growing system will have at least one balancing feedback loop. The reason for this is that sustainability issue systems are often growing in an environment with limited resources. Once the resource runs out, the exponential growth will stop. The exponential growth driven by the reinforcing feedback loops of a system left unchecked will eventually reach a tipping point. A tipping point is where the change in the system being imposed by the reinforcing feedback loops cannot be stopped. This is where the reinforcing feedback loops reach a runaway condition, otherwise known as runaway destruction. The physical system of an extensively discussed sustainability issue we are going to look at in this video is the climate system with the ice albedo or reflectiveness feedback As shown in the diagram the reinforcing feedback loops are shown in yellow and have a plus sign next to them whereas the balancing feedback loops have a minus sign next to them Remember, there must be balancing feedback loops in a physical system because this is working within an environment with finite resources. As the reinforcing feedback loops in the system raise the amount of atmospheric greenhouse gases, this causes a change in the system, starting the exponential growth created by reinforcing feedback loops as shown in the graph. The reinforcing feedback loops then cause an increase in the Earth's global surface temperature. The correlation of these reinforcing feedbacks can also be seen in the graph. However, it is important to remember that systems are complex and that delays are everywhere, hence why the temperature proxy is lagged behind the CO2 emissions. Once the global surface temperature begins to increase, the global surface ice cover begins to decline. The ice cover was previously a balancing feedback loop reflecting the solar radiation back out into space, preventing an increase in global surface temperature. Now that this albedo has become diminished, so does its ability to cool down this global surface temperature. This allows for another reinforcing feedback loop to dominate a balancing one to increase the global surface temperature. Here we can see the reinforcing feedback loops beginning to dominate the system and self their changes This leads to exponential growth of the system chain behaviour and in turn tipping points The ice cover will become so small that there will be more dark surfaces allowing for more solar radiation to be absorbed, causing the global surface temperature to exponentially grow without a dominating balancing feedback loop to keep it near system equilibrium. Left unchecked, this will lead to the tipping point, causing ice that has been there for thousands of years to melt and causing runway collapse, creating a reinforcing feedback loop between other climate systems due to them being dynamic, causing other climate tipping points and preventing the system from ever reaching equilibrium again. A good example of this is Greenland. Due to the increased global surface temperature, the Greenland ice sheet has become unstable beginning to melt with no way of stopping it as the system is in exponential growth moving towards the tipping point. Once this ice sheet has melted so much fresh water will have entered the ocean that it will have substantial impact on the speed of ocean circulation systems causing further tipping points and even runaway collapsing climate. That concludes the video for today and I hope you guys are more clued up on the concept of reinforcing feedback loops and their role. See you next time!",
